	"description": "For most of the history of CSS, selectors have been limited to targeting\nelements based on their parents in the DOM tree. Consider this HTML structure:\n\n&lt;div&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;Paragraph 1&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;div&gt;\n&lt;main&gt;\n    &lt;div&gt;\n    \t&lt;p&gt;Paragraph 2&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n &lt;main&gt;\n\nApplying styles to paragraph 2 in CSS is trivial, as it can be targeted by the\nparent &lt;main&gt; node.\n\nmain p {\n    color: blue;\n}\n\nThis will style Paragraph 2 but not Paragraph 1, as the second paragraph is\ncontained inside the &lt;main&gt; element.\n\nWhat has",
